      • isMergeable

        public boolean isMergeable(ExpressionElement a,
                           ExpressionElement b)
        Description copied from interface: MergeBehavior
        Defines whether an element can be effectively merged with another. If yes, then #mergeElement(MergeBehavior) will be called, computing a new merge from the two elements. 
        
 Note that the interface automatically refuses any merge including two elements from different types.
 Thus no instance check or cast is required inside the method.
        

        

        Specified by:
        

        isMergeable in interface MergeBehavior<ExpressionElement>
        

        Returns:
        

        whether the two elements are mergeable

        mergeElement
        

        public ExpressionElement mergeElement(ExpressionElement a,
                                      ExpressionElement b)
        

        Description copied from interface: MergeBehavior
        

        Computes a defined merge from two elements, which will be added instead of them in the new list.
 The mergeElement method will only be called if the two elements are compatible, and can
 successfully create a new merge.
        

        

        Specified by:
        

        mergeElement in interface MergeBehavior<ExpressionElement>
        

        Returns:
        

        a merge computed from the object itself and the parameter
